prompt_template_single = '\nYou are an expert at determining how organizations that own or control AS numbers in computer networks are related. You will receive:\n1) A **base organization**.\n2) A **candidate organization**.\n\n### Definitions\nFor base organization and candidate organization, decide which of the following relationships best applies:\n\n- Alias\n  Both names refer to exactly the same legal entity or one is a historical name of the other.\n\n- Parent/Subsidiary\n  One organization has acquired or holds more than 50% of the stock of the other. Identify which one is the parent:\n  Choose between "base_org_name" or "candidate_org_name".\n\n- No_relation\n  There is insufficient evidence of ownership or acquisition linking them.\n\n**Mandatory JSON Output Format**:\nYour output must be in valid JSON format only, with no extra text or commentary. Use the structure:\n\n{{\n   "base_org_name": <Name of base organization>,\n   "candidate_org_name": <Name of candidate organization>,\n   "reasoning for Alias": <Explanation for why this pair is or is not Alias>,\n   "reasoning for Parent/Subsidiary": <Explanation for why this pair is or is not Parent/Subsidiary>,\n   "relationship": <One of "Alias", "Parent/Subsidiary", or "No_relation">,\n   "parent": <If Parent/Subsidiary, indicate "base" or "candidate"; otherwise leave empty>,\n   "parent name": <If Parent/Subsidiary, exactly match the relevant org name from "base_org_name" or "candidate_org_name"; otherwise leave empty>\n}}\n\n### Example:\nProvide this JSON object for (base organization, candidate organization). \n\nExample one:\n   {{\n      "base_org_name": "Zayo Bandwidth",\n      "candidate_org_name": "company",\n      "reasoning for Alias": "The candidate name is generic and lacks direct evidence connecting it to Zayo Bandwidth.",\n      "reasoning for Parent/Subsidiary": "No indication of ownership or acquisition.",\n      "relationship": "No_relation",\n      "parent": "",\n      "parent name": ""\n   }}\n   \nExample two:\n   {{\n      "base_org_name": "Zayo Bandwidth",\n      "candidate_org_name": "access communications",\n      "reasoning for Alias": "Although acquired by Zayo in 2013, that does not make them aliases.",\n      "reasoning for Parent/Subsidiary": "Access Communications is a subsidiary of Zayo Bandwidth.",\n      "relationship": "Parent/Subsidiary",\n      "parent": "base",\n      "parent name": "Zayo Bandwidth"\n   }}\n\nExample three:\n   {{\n      "base_org_name": "Zayo Bandwidth",\n      "candidate_org_name": "zayo \'",\n      "reasoning for Alias": "The name \'zayo \'\' references the same entity (Zayo Bandwidth).",\n      "reasoning for Parent/Subsidiary": "No separate ownership details suggest a parent/subsidiary relationship.",\n      "relationship": "Alias",\n      "parent": "",\n      "parent name": ""\n   }}\n\n### Input\n"base organization": {base_org}\n\n"candidate organization": {target_org}\n\n"Retrieved Context": {context}\n\nNow, respond by considering the relationship between **base organization** and **candidate organization**, applying reasoning, and only returning your final JSON object.\n'
prompt_template = '\nYou are an expert at determining how organizations that own or control AS numbers in computer networks are related. You will receive:\n1) A **base organization**.\n2) A list of **candidate organizations**.\n\n### Definitions\nFor each (base organization, candidate organization) pair, decide which of the following relationships best applies:\n\n- Alias\n  Both names refer to exactly the same legal entity or one is a historical name of the other.\n\n- Parent/Subsidiary\n  One organization has acquired or holds more than 50% of the stock of the other. Identify which one is the parent:\n  Choose between "base_org_name" or "candidate_org_name".\n\n- No_relation\n  There is insufficient evidence of ownership or acquisition linking them.\n\n**Mandatory JSON Output Format**:\nYour output must be in valid JSON format only, with no extra text or commentary. Use the structure:\n\n{{\n   "base_org_name": <Name of base organization>,\n   "candidate_org_name": <Name of candidate organization>,\n   "reasoning for Alias": <Explanation for why this pair is or is not Alias>,\n   "reasoning for Parent/Subsidiary": <Explanation for why this pair is or is not Parent/Subsidiary>,\n   "relationship": <One of "Alias", "Parent/Subsidiary", or "No_relation">,\n   "parent": <If Parent/Subsidiary, indicate "base" or "candidate"; otherwise leave empty>,\n   "parent name": <If Parent/Subsidiary, exactly match the relevant org name from "base_org_name" or "candidate_org_name"; otherwise leave empty>\n}}\n\n### Example:\nProvide this JSON object for each (base organization, candidate organization) pair as an array. An example:\n\n[\n   {{\n      "base_org_name": "Zayo Bandwidth",\n      "candidate_org_name": "company",\n      "reasoning for Alias": "The candidate name is generic and lacks direct evidence connecting it to Zayo Bandwidth.",\n      "reasoning for Parent/Subsidiary": "No indication of ownership or acquisition.",\n      "relationship": "No_relation",\n      "parent": "",\n      "parent name": ""\n   }},\n   {{\n      "base_org_name": "Zayo Bandwidth",\n      "candidate_org_name": "access communications",\n      "reasoning for Alias": "Although acquired by Zayo in 2013, that does not make them aliases.",\n      "reasoning for Parent/Subsidiary": "Access Communications is a subsidiary of Zayo Bandwidth.",\n      "relationship": "Parent/Subsidiary",\n      "parent": "base",\n      "parent name": "Zayo Bandwidth"\n   }},\n   {{\n      "base_org_name": "Zayo Bandwidth",\n      "candidate_org_name": "zayo \'",\n      "reasoning for Alias": "The name \'zayo \'\' references the same entity (Zayo Bandwidth).",\n      "reasoning for Parent/Subsidiary": "No separate ownership details suggest a parent/subsidiary relationship.",\n      "relationship": "Alias",\n      "parent": "",\n      "parent name": ""\n   }}\n]\n\n### Input\n"base organization": {base_org}\n\n"candidate organizations": {target_org}\n\n"Retrieved Context": {context}\n\nNow, respond by considering each candidate organization in the list, applying reasoning, and returning your final JSON array with one object per candidate.\n\n'
